## Trade-offs and Rationale

### Architecture Decision Records

#### ADR-001: Modular Monolith vs Microservices

| Decision | Selected: **Modular Monolith** |
|----------|-------------------------------|
| **Rationale** | Team size (5-10 engineers) doesn't justify microservices complexity. Clear module boundaries allow future extraction. |
| **Trade-offs** | + Simpler deployment, lower latency, easier transactions <br>- Harder to scale individual modules, longer build times |
| **Future Path** | Extract AI module to separate service if GPU demand grows; extract HR module for separate compliance deployment |

#### ADR-002: Node.js vs Python vs Go

| Decision | Selected: **Node.js (NestJS)** |
|----------|-------------------------------|
| **Rationale** | TypeScript provides excellent developer experience. Single language across frontend/backend reduces context switching. |
| **Trade-offs** | + Faster development, shared types, large ecosystem <br>- CPU-intensive AI tasks better in Python (separate service) |
| **Future Path** | AI/ML services built in Python (FastAPI) as separate microservices |

#### ADR-003: PostgreSQL vs NoSQL

| Decision | Selected: **PostgreSQL** (with JSONB) |
|----------|---------------------------------------|
| **Rationale** | Appraisal data has complex relationships (users, teams, cycles). ACID compliance critical for audit trails. |
| **Trade-offs** | + Strong consistency, joins, transactions, JSONB flexibility <br>- Vertical scaling limit, more complex sharding |
| **Future Path** | Read replicas for dashboards; TimescaleDB for time-series metrics |

#### ADR-004: Real-time Updates Strategy

| Decision | Selected: **WebSocket + Redis Pub/Sub** |
|----------|----------------------------------------|
| **Rationale** | Managers need immediate notification when AI drafts complete; employees need real-time sync status. |
| **Trade-offs** | + Low latency, bidirectional <br>- Connection management overhead, stateful |
| **Future Path** | Server-Sent Events (SSE) for read-only real-time updates |

#### ADR-005: AI Service Architecture

| Decision | Selected: **Separate Python Microservice** |
|----------|--------------------------------------------|
| **Rationale** | LLM inference, bias detection, and anomaly detection benefit from Python's AI/ML ecosystem (PyTorch, scikit-learn, LangChain). |
| **Trade-offs** | + Best AI libraries, independent scaling, isolated failures <br>- Network latency, additional operational complexity |
| **Future Path** | Consider serverless (AWS Lambda) for sporadic AI inference |

## Scalability & High Availability

### Scaling Strategy

| Component | Scaling Method | Target |
|-----------|---------------|--------|
| Frontend SPA | CDN + Static hosting | Global edge caching |
| API Gateway | Horizontal pods (HPA) | 10k+ req/sec |
| Backend Modules | Horizontal pods (HPA) | Based on CPU/memory |
| AI Service | GPU-backed horizontal scaling | Queue-based autoscaling |
| PostgreSQL | Read replicas + connection pooling | 1M+ active users |
| Redis Cluster | Sharded cluster | 100k+ concurrent sessions |
| Message Queue | Partitioned queues | 1M+ messages/hour |

